WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.281 --> 00:00:03.610
- Good evening, everyone.

00:00:03.610 --> 00:00:04.350
I'm Liz Cohen.

00:00:04.350 --> 00:00:06.690
I'm Dean of the Radcliffe
Institute for Advanced Study,

00:00:06.690 --> 00:00:10.440
and it's my pleasure to
welcome you to tonight's show

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:15.840
and tell exploration of
citizenship, gender, and film.

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:19.140
This program kicks off our
Annual Gender Conference,

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:23.280
which is focused this year
on the topic, "Who belongs?

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:28.340
Global Citizenship and
Gender in the 21st Century."

00:00:28.340 --> 00:00:31.970
Before we dive in, I'd like
to thank all of our speakers

00:00:31.970 --> 00:00:33.800
for joining us tonight.

00:00:33.800 --> 00:00:36.770
And, again, tomorrow
they'll be another crew.

00:00:36.770 --> 00:00:40.460
I'm also grateful to Rebecca
Wassarman, Executive Director

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:42.860
of Academic Ventures,
Jessica Viklund,

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:44.810
the Director of
Radcliffe Events,

00:00:44.810 --> 00:00:47.150
and their fantastic teams.

00:00:47.150 --> 00:00:49.310
Thanks as well to
Dan Carpenter, who

00:00:49.310 --> 00:00:52.880
chaired the Faculty Organizing
Committee for the conference,

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:56.210
and to committee members,
Professors Sara Bleich,

00:00:56.210 --> 00:00:59.660
Melanie Cammett, Jane
Kamensky, Michele Lemont,

00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:00.980
and Mark Tushnet.

00:01:00.980 --> 00:01:02.750
And, finally,
thanks to all of you

00:01:02.750 --> 00:01:05.500
for joining us here tonight.

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:08.410
Every spring, we
organize this conference

00:01:08.410 --> 00:01:12.160
to address an issue of
broad public concern

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:14.380
through the lens of gender.

00:01:14.380 --> 00:01:16.720
In recent years we
have examined topics

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:20.740
such as sports, language,
violence, and public health,

00:01:20.740 --> 00:01:23.200
to name just a few.

00:01:23.200 --> 00:01:25.810
This annual conference
is one manifestation

00:01:25.810 --> 00:01:27.760
of Radcliffe's
founding commitment

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:30.310
to the study of
gender and society,

00:01:30.310 --> 00:01:32.590
which we trace
back to our legacy

00:01:32.590 --> 00:01:36.390
as the institutional descendant
of Radcliffe College.

00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:39.910
Today, as Harvard's
Institute for Advanced Study,

00:01:39.910 --> 00:01:43.390
Radcliffe provides a vibrant
interdisciplinary forum,

00:01:43.390 --> 00:01:45.730
and convenes leading
thinkers working

00:01:45.730 --> 00:01:48.880
at the forefront of all fields.

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:51.610
Each year we open
our gender conference

00:01:51.610 --> 00:01:55.020
with an evening
dedicated to the arts.

00:01:55.020 --> 00:01:58.900
And we do this to fulfill
another core commitment, which

00:01:58.900 --> 00:02:02.710
is the integration of the
creative arts with other forms

00:02:02.710 --> 00:02:04.720
of scholarly inquiry.

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:08.620
We begin with the arts because
artistic expression compels

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:12.520
us to consider challenging
issues, like citizenship,

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:15.040
from a unique vantage point.

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:18.070
Tonight we are joined by
three talented filmmakers,

00:02:18.070 --> 00:02:20.530
and a distinguished
critic, who will engage

00:02:20.530 --> 00:02:22.870
in a discussion about
the power of film

00:02:22.870 --> 00:02:25.900
to shape our understanding
of citizenship and gender

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:28.010
in important ways.

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:32.090
Film portrayals, both
fictional and documentary,

00:02:32.090 --> 00:02:35.540
can bring to life the
complexity of citizenship,

00:02:35.540 --> 00:02:40.350
and can show us its relationship
to belonging and exclusion.

00:02:40.350 --> 00:02:44.400
These issues inform our
everyday experiences.

00:02:44.400 --> 00:02:48.470
So what better medium than
film to capture and elucidate

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:52.930
how individuals navigate
this lived reality?

00:02:52.930 --> 00:02:57.310
Whether films are shown on
the big screen of a theater,

00:02:57.310 --> 00:03:00.220
viewed on a college
campus, or watched

00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:04.450
on a television in our homes,
they offer us a unique entry

00:03:04.450 --> 00:03:08.770
point into how our society
understands citizenship

00:03:08.770 --> 00:03:10.720
and national identity.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:15.900
And films also shape that
societal understanding.

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:20.340
One infamous example
is the 1915 film

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:25.380
The Birth of a Nation, a silent
film directed by D.W. Griffith.

00:03:25.380 --> 00:03:29.160
Premiering under the
original title, The Clansman,

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:32.580
this film presented a
three-hour dramatization

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:35.550
of white supremacist
ideology told

00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:38.430
through the lives of two
intertwined families, one

00:03:38.430 --> 00:03:41.520
Northern and one Southern,
during the Civil War

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:43.550
and into Reconstruction.

00:03:43.550 --> 00:03:47.310
The film romanticized the Ku
Klux Klan as a healing force

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:50.220
for the South, and it
depicted black people

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:52.890
in overtly racist
caricatures that became

00:03:52.890 --> 00:03:55.800
widespread and deeply harmful.

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:58.800
The Birth of a Nation
also had a profound impact

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:01.710
on the nascent film
industry largely because

00:04:01.710 --> 00:04:05.860
of its immense popularity
among white audiences.

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:12.130
In reaction to the film in 1915,
the Boston branch of the NAACP

00:04:12.130 --> 00:04:16.240
published a 47-page booklet
condemning the film,

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:19.269
and showing a keen
awareness of the threat it

00:04:19.269 --> 00:04:21.950
posed to black citizenship.

00:04:21.950 --> 00:04:24.370
They wrote, and I
quote, "We believe

00:04:24.370 --> 00:04:29.050
this film teaches a propaganda
for the purpose of so stirring

00:04:29.050 --> 00:04:33.010
up the people of the East
and the West and the North,

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:34.990
that they would
consent to allowing

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:37.840
the Southern program
of disenfranchisement,

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:40.810
segregation, and
lynching of the Negro.

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:45.810
And finally to the repeal of
the 14th and 15th Amendments."

00:04:45.810 --> 00:04:48.910
In the 100-plus years
since that first screening

00:04:48.910 --> 00:04:52.090
of The Birth of a
Nation, mainstream films

00:04:52.090 --> 00:04:56.590
have continued to reinforce
ahistorical storylines and

00:04:56.590 --> 00:05:01.150
damaging stereotypes,
whether intentionally or not.

00:05:01.150 --> 00:05:04.060
Still today, widely
distributed films

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:09.100
tend to reflect a narrow
white and male experience.

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:11.590
According to research
out of the University

00:05:11.590 --> 00:05:13.330
of Southern
California's Annenberg

00:05:13.330 --> 00:05:15.910
School for Communication
and Journalism,

00:05:15.910 --> 00:05:23.500
in the top 100 highest-grossing
films of 2016, less than a 1/3

00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:26.230
of all speaking
characters were women.

00:05:26.230 --> 00:05:27.910
That's pretty stunning.

00:05:27.910 --> 00:05:31.930
Some 70% of all
characters were white.

00:05:31.930 --> 00:05:33.640
Even more stunning.

00:05:33.640 --> 00:05:37.750
And a 1/4 of these same films
featured no black speaking

00:05:37.750 --> 00:05:41.320
characters, while over
1/2 lacked Latino speaking

00:05:41.320 --> 00:05:43.230
characters.

00:05:43.230 --> 00:05:47.190
Representation is important
both in front of the camera,

00:05:47.190 --> 00:05:49.020
and behind it.

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:53.040
I doubt it will surprise anyone
in this room that increasing

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:56.070
diversity among
directors and producers

00:05:56.070 --> 00:06:00.780
also remains difficult. The
people in those roles shape

00:06:00.780 --> 00:06:04.140
which stories are
told, what we learn,

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:07.740
and how we collectively
think about important issues.

00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:13.170
Felix Contreras, who is the
host of the weekly NPR program

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:15.660
Alt.Latino, lamented
in the run-up

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:19.650
to the recent Academy Awards,
and I quote, "Very often we

00:06:19.650 --> 00:06:23.400
have to leave the studios
of the Hollywood ecosystem,

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:25.950
and enter the world
of independent film

00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:30.540
to find the diverse communities
that we actually live in."

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:33.810
Issues of representation
and portrayal in film

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:37.080
are closely connected to
the question, who belongs,

00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:39.420
that animates our conference.

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:43.290
The litany of challenges
is clear, but so too is

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:46.920
the potential for
storytelling through film

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:49.770
to serve as a positive force.

00:06:49.770 --> 00:06:53.370
I'm delighted that we have such
an outstanding group of experts

00:06:53.370 --> 00:06:56.190
with us tonight to
explore these issues,

00:06:56.190 --> 00:07:00.390
and to consider whose
stories get told, by whom,

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:02.040
and for whom.

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:06.720
Gender is our particular
concern over the next 24 hours,

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:11.220
but I'm sure it will come quite
clear that sexual identity is

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:16.010
deeply intertwined with
race, ethnicity, and class.

00:07:16.010 --> 00:07:19.340
Claudia Puig will moderate
tonight's discussion between

00:07:19.340 --> 00:07:23.360
filmmakers Maria Agui
Carter, Heather Courtney,

00:07:23.360 --> 00:07:25.440
and Cynthia López.

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:28.650
Claudia is a nationally
recognized film journalist,

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:32.370
the president of the Los Angeles
Film Critics Association,

00:07:32.370 --> 00:07:35.550
and a movie critic
for NPR'S FilmWeek.

00:07:35.550 --> 00:07:39.720
She's also the former lead
film critic for USA Today.

00:07:39.720 --> 00:07:42.000
Claudia will introduce
the panelists,

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.460
and you can read full
biographies of everyone

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:47.340
in your printed program.

00:07:47.340 --> 00:07:50.150
Before Claudia and our
panel come up to the stage,

00:07:50.150 --> 00:07:54.070
I just want to give you a
quick note about logistics.

00:07:54.070 --> 00:07:58.200
We'll hear and see presentations
from all the panelists,

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:00.090
and then Claudia
will engage them

00:08:00.090 --> 00:08:02.280
in conversation as a group.

00:08:02.280 --> 00:08:04.260
And following that
discussion, we

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:06.800
will open up the floor
to your questions.

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:09.180
We'll place a microphone
in the center aisle.

00:08:09.180 --> 00:08:11.370
You're invited to
join the conversation,

00:08:11.370 --> 00:08:15.180
but please identify yourself
before you ask your question.

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:17.790
I also hope to see many
of you again tomorrow

00:08:17.790 --> 00:08:20.190
morning when the
conference continues

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:22.680
in this room at 9:00 AM.

00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:27.000
So now please join me in giving
a warm welcome to our speakers

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:29.346
as they come up to the stage.

00:08:29.346 --> 00:08:38.806
[CLAPPING]

00:08:39.306 --> 00:08:43.390
- Hi, everybody.

00:08:43.390 --> 00:08:45.410
I'll begin with just
a couple of remarks,

00:08:45.410 --> 00:08:48.590
and then we will go through
with each of us speaking.

00:08:48.590 --> 00:08:50.600
And then we'll have
a joint conversation,

00:08:50.600 --> 00:08:52.700
and then we'll
open it up to you.

00:08:55.684 --> 00:08:57.350
I want to talk about,
just for a moment,

00:08:57.350 --> 00:09:03.134
about the power of film to
broaden us, and to educate.

00:09:03.134 --> 00:09:04.550
How many of you've
watched a movie

00:09:04.550 --> 00:09:06.200
that opened your
eyes to something

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:07.475
you knew very little about?

00:09:07.475 --> 00:09:09.350
Raise your hand if you've
seen the movie that

00:09:09.350 --> 00:09:13.460
broadened your knowledge
in the past six months.

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:15.050
OK, good.

00:09:15.050 --> 00:09:17.210
People often talk about
escaping into films,

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:20.780
but films also escape into us.

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:24.950
They open our eyes, and they
help us understand ourselves.

00:09:24.950 --> 00:09:27.020
They help us understand
our fellow human beings.

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:28.650
They reveal us to
ourselves, and reveal

00:09:28.650 --> 00:09:30.960
the experiences of others.

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:34.510
The best films connect us
to our shared humanity.

00:09:34.510 --> 00:09:35.920
Films are all about revelation.

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:37.540
They illustrate the
human experience

00:09:37.540 --> 00:09:42.484
in all its glory, messiness,
complexity, and fullness.

00:09:42.484 --> 00:09:44.650
Movies provide a window
into the magnificent breadth

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:46.940
of who we are, often
exploring the lives of people

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:49.400
we might otherwise never know.

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:51.650
Films can lay bare the deepest
emotions, and innermost

00:09:51.650 --> 00:09:55.430
thoughts of others, providing a
uniquely revelatory experience.

00:09:55.430 --> 00:09:57.950
Films work on our hearts
and minds on so many levels,

00:09:57.950 --> 00:10:01.070
engaging and moving us in
conscious and subconscious

00:10:01.070 --> 00:10:03.425
ways.

00:10:03.425 --> 00:10:05.050
Their images make a
powerful impression

00:10:05.050 --> 00:10:07.130
and stay with us, sometimes
throughout our lives.

00:10:07.130 --> 00:10:10.130
If I were to go around the
room and asked you to come up

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:12.680
with an iconic
image from a film,

00:10:12.680 --> 00:10:14.510
you'd have no trouble
coming up with it.

00:10:14.510 --> 00:10:16.879
What makes it even
better is that the

00:10:16.879 --> 00:10:18.920
what made those deep
impressions will probably be

00:10:18.920 --> 00:10:20.570
different for everybody here.

00:10:23.420 --> 00:10:25.160
I immediately thought
of the little girl

00:10:25.160 --> 00:10:27.590
in the red coat in
Schindler's List,

00:10:27.590 --> 00:10:29.990
and all the black
and white around her.

00:10:29.990 --> 00:10:32.450
The chess game between
the knight and death

00:10:32.450 --> 00:10:34.190
in Seventh Seal.

00:10:34.190 --> 00:10:36.149
Howard Beale screaming,
I'm mad as hell

00:10:36.149 --> 00:10:37.940
and I'm not going to
take it anymore, which

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:41.240
seems appropriate these days.

00:10:41.240 --> 00:10:44.060
So images on screen
seep into our pores,

00:10:44.060 --> 00:10:47.500
they burrow under our skin,
they live on in our minds.

00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:51.380
Films engage us orally,
emotionally, intellectually.

00:10:51.380 --> 00:10:53.750
The combined effects of
cinematography, score,

00:10:53.750 --> 00:10:55.770
dialogue, sound
design, and of course,

00:10:55.770 --> 00:10:58.130
the characters themselves,
provide lasting images

00:10:58.130 --> 00:11:00.200
that we often
compare to real life.

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:02.420
Sometimes real life
feels like a movie.

00:11:02.420 --> 00:11:04.874
The best movies
feel like real life.

00:11:04.874 --> 00:11:06.290
The three filmmakers
whose work we

00:11:06.290 --> 00:11:08.840
are so fortunate to be
exploring here tonight

00:11:08.840 --> 00:11:11.462
offer just that kind
of deep revelation.

00:11:11.462 --> 00:11:12.920
The process of
watching their films

00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:14.960
is almost like excavation.

00:11:14.960 --> 00:11:17.660
They mine their own experiences,
and those of others,

00:11:17.660 --> 00:11:19.580
grappling with
adapting to society.

00:11:19.580 --> 00:11:21.830
Their work digs deeply
into the fraught process

00:11:21.830 --> 00:11:24.881
of emigrating and acclimating
to a new environment.

00:11:24.881 --> 00:11:26.630
Watching films like
those of our panelists

00:11:26.630 --> 00:11:29.340
can help us understand
one another.

00:11:29.340 --> 00:11:32.750
They can help us keep
from seeing those who

00:11:32.750 --> 00:11:36.470
are not like us as the "other."

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:39.475
They remind us that we are
all citizens of the world,

00:11:39.475 --> 00:11:41.600
and as such, we have more
in common with each other

00:11:41.600 --> 00:11:43.060
than we have differences.

00:11:43.060 --> 00:11:45.560
By delving into portrayals like
the ones we're about to see,

00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:48.170
we can better understand,
empathize with, and ideally,

00:11:48.170 --> 00:11:52.160
help one another in our
common global citizenship.

00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:54.470
And as we recognize our
commonalities as human beings,

00:11:54.470 --> 00:11:56.870
we get a clearer sense of
what others experience,

00:11:56.870 --> 00:11:58.100
the barriers they face--

00:11:58.100 --> 00:12:01.490
whether literal walls, or
psychological and cultural

00:12:01.490 --> 00:12:03.140
obstacles.

00:12:03.140 --> 00:12:06.080
I was thinking that the word
"citizenship"-- and citizenship

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:09.940
means so much more than
living within certain borders.

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:13.400
When we were all in grade school
it meant behaving responsibly.

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:15.340
You get a citizenship
grade, and that

00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:18.280
pertained to our behavior,
our human decency,

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:20.140
even as children.

00:12:20.140 --> 00:12:22.312
So good citizens are human
beings who behave well.

00:12:22.312 --> 00:12:24.020
They care for their
brothers and sisters,

00:12:24.020 --> 00:12:26.900
and they make the
world a better place.

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:29.840
Films can offer us that portal
to being better citizens,

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:31.610
more exemplary humans.

00:12:31.610 --> 00:12:33.380
The best films go
beyond the obvious

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:36.110
and deepen our understanding,
challenge our expectations,

00:12:36.110 --> 00:12:38.150
and reshape our preconceptions.

00:12:38.150 --> 00:12:41.270
They illuminate and
elucidate, and in the process,

00:12:41.270 --> 00:12:43.240
encourage essential compassion.

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:45.922
In the best cases,
they can transform us.

00:12:45.922 --> 00:12:47.630
I'm very grateful to
be here in this room

00:12:47.630 --> 00:12:50.600
as we ask today and
tomorrow, who belongs?

00:12:50.600 --> 00:12:54.080
The answer as I see
it is, we all do.

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:55.640
And films powerfully
and passionately

00:12:55.640 --> 00:12:58.820
make our global sense of
community abundantly clear.

00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:01.460
So I'm happy to be hosting this
opening panel on citizenship

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:03.860
and gender as viewed
through the lens

00:13:03.860 --> 00:13:07.340
of masterful cinematic
storytellers.

00:13:07.340 --> 00:13:09.980
I'm delighted to introduce
you to Cynthia López,

00:13:09.980 --> 00:13:12.560
Heather Courtney,
Maria Agui Carter,

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:14.981
and they will each show clips
from their impressive body

00:13:14.981 --> 00:13:15.480
of work.

00:13:15.480 --> 00:13:16.604
So I'll start with Cynthia.

00:13:16.604 --> 00:13:17.900
- Hi, good evening.

00:13:17.900 --> 00:13:22.130
I think I'm going to stand at
the podium a couple of minutes.

00:13:22.130 --> 00:13:24.830
And I'd first like to say
that I'm thrilled to be here

00:13:24.830 --> 00:13:28.910
this evening to be part of
this conversation, citizenship,

00:13:28.910 --> 00:13:30.650
gender, and film.

00:13:30.650 --> 00:13:36.050
I'd like to thank you, Dean
Elizabeth Cohen, Rebecca

00:13:36.050 --> 00:13:38.600
Wassarman, and Maria Agui
Carter for inviting me

00:13:38.600 --> 00:13:42.050
this evening to share some
insights and some experiences.

00:13:42.050 --> 00:13:45.290
During my past 25 years,
I've had the privilege

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:49.280
to be a library advocate raising
money for the nation's poorest

00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:50.450
libraries.

00:13:50.450 --> 00:13:52.760
Then I turned, and I
was executive producer

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:55.220
of the award-winning
series, POV.

00:13:55.220 --> 00:13:57.440
And, most recently, I
was film commissioner

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:00.680
of New York City, where I
was the steward of the media

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:03.170
and entertainment
business industry.

00:14:03.170 --> 00:14:07.310
To begin, I'd like to share with
you a transformational moment

00:14:07.310 --> 00:14:10.760
in my life, and tell you
a little bit about myself.

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:14.900
I call it "Rosary
Beads and Sundance."

00:14:14.900 --> 00:14:19.490
In 2005, it had snowed
more than 20 inches,

00:14:19.490 --> 00:14:23.300
and I had anxiously arrived
at the Salt Lake City airport.

00:14:23.300 --> 00:14:24.920
I was going to New York City.

00:14:24.920 --> 00:14:26.570
I was making it home.

00:14:26.570 --> 00:14:30.560
I had just attended the
Sundance Film Festival.

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:32.570
I had one of those
rare moments that you

00:14:32.570 --> 00:14:35.600
have in your career, where
you feel accomplished.

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:37.400
And I kept on
thinking, this is what

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:41.120
it feels like to be
a star quarterback,

00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:46.670
running that last stretch right
before you have that touchdown.

00:14:46.670 --> 00:14:48.080
I felt just like that.

00:14:48.080 --> 00:14:50.780
I had met with all the
filmmakers I wanted to meet.

00:14:50.780 --> 00:14:53.210
I had all the business
meetings I wanted to do.

00:14:53.210 --> 00:14:56.840
I successfully completed, and
I actually saw some films,

00:14:56.840 --> 00:14:59.120
at Sundance, too.

00:14:59.120 --> 00:15:02.580
And now, even though I
was thoroughly exhausted,

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:05.900
I had to get on this flight,
and get to the Reuters studio

00:15:05.900 --> 00:15:08.510
at 6:00 AM the next day.

00:15:08.510 --> 00:15:11.390
I was meeting Gloria Steinem.

00:15:11.390 --> 00:15:13.850
I had reached out
to her and asked

00:15:13.850 --> 00:15:18.380
her, could she help us promote
a film directed by Shola Lynch,

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:22.190
called Chisholm '72, which
was about Shirley Chisholm,

00:15:22.190 --> 00:15:25.730
the first black woman to run for
President of the United States.

00:15:25.730 --> 00:15:28.580
My cell phone rang, and
it was my colleague.

00:15:28.580 --> 00:15:31.860
And all I could hear her say,
flights are being canceled,

00:15:31.860 --> 00:15:33.650
I'm very concerned.

00:15:33.650 --> 00:15:35.610
Maybe you won't
be in the studio.

00:15:35.610 --> 00:15:39.230
Maybe we'll lose this string
of interviews that you set up.

00:15:39.230 --> 00:15:41.380
Before my cell
phone died, I heard

00:15:41.380 --> 00:15:46.460
Cynthia, I canceled flight,
was able to purchase a business

00:15:46.460 --> 00:15:47.480
class ticket.

00:15:47.480 --> 00:15:50.540
Get to counter immediately.

00:15:50.540 --> 00:15:53.930
I ran frantically with my
carry-ons, and my Sundance

00:15:53.930 --> 00:15:56.150
bags, and my heavy snow boots.

00:15:56.150 --> 00:15:57.410
I was a wreck.

00:15:57.410 --> 00:16:00.050
An absolute wreck.

00:16:00.050 --> 00:16:01.610
All of the sudden,
I thought, how

00:16:01.610 --> 00:16:05.480
can I go from being
that quarterback,

00:16:05.480 --> 00:16:09.200
to totally feeling
demoralized and absolutely

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:10.850
with nothing left?

00:16:10.850 --> 00:16:13.550
But, oh my god, I have
to get on this plane.

00:16:13.550 --> 00:16:16.040
And all I kept on
thinking was, nothing

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:20.090
will change and diminish
this moment, because I will

00:16:20.090 --> 00:16:22.070
meet Gloria Steinem tomorrow.

00:16:22.070 --> 00:16:25.210
No matter what.

00:16:25.210 --> 00:16:27.910
When I was a kid, I went
to all these marches.

00:16:27.910 --> 00:16:30.100
My mother and I-- she
wanted to teach me.

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:32.110
You have to fight for equality.

00:16:32.110 --> 00:16:34.060
You have to fight for justice.

00:16:34.060 --> 00:16:37.840
These things won't come
to you, unless you work.

00:16:37.840 --> 00:16:41.420
I was looking down in
a haze of exhaustion,

00:16:41.420 --> 00:16:45.490
when two US patrol
officers started

00:16:45.490 --> 00:16:48.310
walking up and down the aisles.

00:16:48.310 --> 00:16:52.150
And people were lined up to do
the final security checkpoints.

00:16:52.150 --> 00:16:56.710
And then, as if I was the
central character of a Lifetime

00:16:56.710 --> 00:17:03.160
movie special, I heard, Cynthia
López, please step out of line.

00:17:03.160 --> 00:17:06.130
You were wanted for inspection.

00:17:06.130 --> 00:17:13.119
Cynthia López, step out of line,
you were wanted for inspection.

00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:18.010
And as I saw the patrol officers
walk near, I kept thinking,

00:17:18.010 --> 00:17:19.540
this can't be happening.

00:17:19.540 --> 00:17:21.609
This just cannot be happening.

00:17:21.609 --> 00:17:26.520
I was terrorized, and for a
quick second, I said to myself,

00:17:26.520 --> 00:17:30.460
did I have a jelly
donut in my backpack?

00:17:30.460 --> 00:17:32.650
Did I have extra sugar?

00:17:32.650 --> 00:17:35.380
Was it my Chinese
herbs that somehow

00:17:35.380 --> 00:17:37.510
look weird to the inspectors?

00:17:37.510 --> 00:17:41.680
What had I done to
engender an inspection?

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:46.210
Frantically, I started
saying, why are you taking me?

00:17:46.210 --> 00:17:47.240
I'm an American.

00:17:47.240 --> 00:17:48.490
I'm a citizen.

00:17:48.490 --> 00:17:50.860
I was born in this country.

00:17:50.860 --> 00:17:52.330
Sit down, ma'am.

00:17:52.330 --> 00:17:55.690
Please be quiet,
and do not move.

00:17:55.690 --> 00:18:00.940
Sit here, and someone will come
and ask you a few questions.

00:18:00.940 --> 00:18:02.710
I have to get on this flight.

00:18:02.710 --> 00:18:04.630
Can you please call PBS?

00:18:04.630 --> 00:18:05.860
Call my superior.

00:18:05.860 --> 00:18:08.260
Call the Sundance Festival.

00:18:08.260 --> 00:18:10.060
They'll vouch for me, really.

00:18:10.060 --> 00:18:11.890
I'm an American.

00:18:11.890 --> 00:18:16.300
They opened my luggage and took
everything out, piece by piece

00:18:16.300 --> 00:18:17.680
by piece.

00:18:17.680 --> 00:18:19.960
And I have to say,
if anyone could

00:18:19.960 --> 00:18:23.890
have an internal nervous
breakdown, I had one that day.

00:18:23.890 --> 00:18:25.690
For sure.

00:18:25.690 --> 00:18:29.170
Please call the main office
at Sundance, I pleaded.

00:18:29.170 --> 00:18:30.400
Please.

00:18:30.400 --> 00:18:34.130
You can even see the
program in my luggage.

00:18:34.130 --> 00:18:36.330
Ma'am, do not get excitable.

00:18:36.330 --> 00:18:38.860
There is nothing to
get excited about.

00:18:38.860 --> 00:18:42.310
You don't need to get anxious.

00:18:42.310 --> 00:18:45.310
I was having an
out-of-body experience,

00:18:45.310 --> 00:18:48.190
and I understood that
everything that we

00:18:48.190 --> 00:18:51.700
had to contend with at the
time was the extra security

00:18:51.700 --> 00:18:52.540
measures.

00:18:52.540 --> 00:18:57.100
If you remember I
said this was 2005.

00:18:57.100 --> 00:18:59.770
My stepsister works in
the financial industry.

00:18:59.770 --> 00:19:02.770
Hell, I understand
that we all have

00:19:02.770 --> 00:19:05.830
to deal with extra security.

00:19:05.830 --> 00:19:08.980
Thankfully, her office
was on the 68th floor

00:19:08.980 --> 00:19:10.450
of the World Trade Center.

00:19:10.450 --> 00:19:13.210
Thankfully, she was
not there that day.

00:19:13.210 --> 00:19:16.720
But I understand,
as an American,

00:19:16.720 --> 00:19:19.090
we have to take precautions.

00:19:19.090 --> 00:19:22.000
When I heard the
woman inspectors say,

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:26.890
she looks Syrian, we have
to take all precautions.

00:19:26.890 --> 00:19:28.420
I died inside.

00:19:28.420 --> 00:19:30.620
And I said, I'm from Brooklyn.

00:19:30.620 --> 00:19:32.960
I am from Brooklyn.

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:35.380
I am an American.

00:19:35.380 --> 00:19:36.820
As she looked
through my luggage,

00:19:36.820 --> 00:19:40.450
she found rosary beads that
I had purchased in Italy,

00:19:40.450 --> 00:19:44.050
and I had joked with my brother,
these will protect my luggage

00:19:44.050 --> 00:19:46.210
from ever being stolen.

00:19:46.210 --> 00:19:50.140
The agent then asked,
are you Catholic?

00:19:50.140 --> 00:19:54.460
And for a second I said, I'm
actually Episcopalian now.

00:19:54.460 --> 00:19:55.980
And then I caught
myself and said,

00:19:55.980 --> 00:19:58.115
absolutely I'm a
registered Catholic.

00:20:01.610 --> 00:20:05.540
Joe, call Sundance and see
if they can vouch for her.

00:20:05.540 --> 00:20:09.460
My hands were shaking,
and I kept thinking,

00:20:09.460 --> 00:20:11.890
I'm not from another country.

00:20:11.890 --> 00:20:15.160
But when they asked me where I
was from, and I said Brooklyn,

00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:18.010
they didn't really like that.

00:20:18.010 --> 00:20:21.010
But where are your
parents from, they said.

00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:25.030
I snapped back, well my
father is from Puerto Rico,

00:20:25.030 --> 00:20:27.190
and my mother is
from Long Island.

00:20:27.190 --> 00:20:30.490
All your family is
from another country.

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:34.240
I was terrorized again,
but I tried to explain,

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:38.320
well actually Puerto Rico is a
territory of the United States.

00:20:38.320 --> 00:20:40.990
It's like Guam or
the Virgin Islands,

00:20:40.990 --> 00:20:43.930
and a few other islands
that the US owns,

00:20:43.930 --> 00:20:46.000
that they usually get
from wars that they have,

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:48.490
and Puerto Rico specifically
came from Spain.

00:20:48.490 --> 00:20:51.250
And then I caught myself,
and I remembered my oh

00:20:51.250 --> 00:20:55.720
my mother always saying,
just answer the question.

00:20:55.720 --> 00:20:58.480
And I became quiet.

00:20:58.480 --> 00:21:02.140
The male patrol guard
came back and he said,

00:21:02.140 --> 00:21:04.270
the Sundance office
vouched for her.

00:21:04.270 --> 00:21:06.100
She's legit.

00:21:06.100 --> 00:21:09.160
Ma'am, do you understand
why we brought you

00:21:09.160 --> 00:21:11.230
to the security check?

00:21:11.230 --> 00:21:14.350
Do you understand,
ma'am, why you're here?

00:21:14.350 --> 00:21:16.330
And I was shaking
because I thought,

00:21:16.330 --> 00:21:17.680
I didn't bring my passport.

00:21:17.680 --> 00:21:19.900
I just had my driver's ID.

00:21:19.900 --> 00:21:23.080
But I always used my
driver's ID to travel.

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:24.860
Well let me explain.

00:21:24.860 --> 00:21:28.090
You canceled your flight,
purchased another ticket,

00:21:28.090 --> 00:21:31.240
and it was all through a
third party in New York.

00:21:31.240 --> 00:21:34.060
And your luggage is on the
other plane, and truth be told,

00:21:34.060 --> 00:21:36.280
you don't look like
you're an American.

00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:39.490
Plus our cameras picked up
that you look pretty frantic

00:21:39.490 --> 00:21:40.750
in the lobby.

00:21:40.750 --> 00:21:41.680
What were you doing?

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:43.840
What were you looking for?

00:21:43.840 --> 00:21:47.030
And I tried not to engage.

00:21:47.030 --> 00:21:48.880
I kept my head down,
and I just thought,

00:21:48.880 --> 00:21:50.950
I have to get on the plane.

00:21:50.950 --> 00:21:54.490
I am meeting Gloria
Steinem, I said in my head.

00:21:54.490 --> 00:21:58.880
I was looking for an
outlet to plug my phone.

00:21:58.880 --> 00:22:01.220
That's what I was doing, I said.

00:22:01.220 --> 00:22:01.930
Well, no problem.

00:22:01.930 --> 00:22:04.570
We'll run you over to the plane.

00:22:04.570 --> 00:22:06.640
When I ran through the
terminal with the two

00:22:06.640 --> 00:22:08.180
agents and the dogs--

00:22:08.180 --> 00:22:12.700
they escorted me to my
business class ticket--

00:22:12.700 --> 00:22:14.950
I felt devastated.

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:17.620
Ms. López, on behalf
of the US government,

00:22:17.620 --> 00:22:20.890
we deeply apologize for any
inconvenience this may have

00:22:20.890 --> 00:22:22.660
caused.

00:22:22.660 --> 00:22:25.300
When they said that, all
the other passengers looked

00:22:25.300 --> 00:22:28.010
at me like, what had I done?

00:22:28.010 --> 00:22:33.760
And if you know me, I'm a very
actually quiet, shy person.

00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:36.430
Please have a good day, he said.

00:22:36.430 --> 00:22:38.930
I nodded out of compliance.

00:22:38.930 --> 00:22:42.310
I just put my head
down, and I was shaking.

00:22:42.310 --> 00:22:45.640
And I finally cried
uncontrollably

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:48.100
when the airplane doors closed.

00:22:48.100 --> 00:22:50.590
And all I could
think of was lots

00:22:50.590 --> 00:22:56.050
of people get trapped like
this every single day.

00:22:56.050 --> 00:22:59.450
And I just felt
like it wasn't over.

00:22:59.450 --> 00:23:01.810
And now every time
I go to the airport,

00:23:01.810 --> 00:23:06.790
my heart flutters until I
pass the final security points

00:23:06.790 --> 00:23:11.380
because I never want my
citizenship, or my identity,

00:23:11.380 --> 00:23:14.440
to ever be confused.

00:23:14.440 --> 00:23:17.530
So I will not take the
remaining couple of minutes

00:23:17.530 --> 00:23:20.960
that I have to give you a
Puerto Rican history lesson,

00:23:20.960 --> 00:23:24.430
but there are a couple of
things I do want to say.

00:23:24.430 --> 00:23:30.070
Puerto Rico was acquired by
the United States in 1898.

00:23:30.070 --> 00:23:36.730
Puerto Ricans are US citizens
since the Jones Act in 1917.

00:23:36.730 --> 00:23:40.090
And the US wanted to ensure that
Puerto Rican men participate

00:23:40.090 --> 00:23:42.490
in all US wars.

00:23:42.490 --> 00:23:45.070
Puerto Rico is a commonwealth
of the United States,

00:23:45.070 --> 00:23:48.600
which means that Puerto
Ricans are US citizens,

00:23:48.600 --> 00:23:51.970
but we cannot vote for the
President of the United States

00:23:51.970 --> 00:23:54.820
unless you live on the mainland.

00:23:54.820 --> 00:23:57.220
Currently, the Puerto
Rican government, not

00:23:57.220 --> 00:24:02.590
the Puerto Rican people,
owe $72 billion in debt.

00:24:02.590 --> 00:24:04.630
And the US federal
government is currently

00:24:04.630 --> 00:24:08.270
deciding how that
debt should be paid.

00:24:08.270 --> 00:24:11.470
And due to Hurricane Maria,
the Puerto Rican debt crisis,

00:24:11.470 --> 00:24:14.170
Puerto Ricans on the
island are facing

00:24:14.170 --> 00:24:19.433
the worst humanitarian
crisis in its history.

00:24:19.433 --> 00:24:22.390
450 Puerto Rican people
have left the island

00:24:22.390 --> 00:24:24.580
over the last year and a half.

00:24:24.580 --> 00:24:27.770
And recently-- I have to say,
in doing research for this panel

00:24:27.770 --> 00:24:29.980
and also for a project
I'm working on--

00:24:29.980 --> 00:24:32.920
I learned that the Harvard
Student Labor Movement,

00:24:32.920 --> 00:24:36.520
along with activists from
Hedge Clippers, and others,

00:24:36.520 --> 00:24:40.480
marched here at Harvard
Yard, protesting

00:24:40.480 --> 00:24:42.640
in support of divestment.

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:46.240
Because the Harvard endowment,
which currently totals

00:24:46.240 --> 00:24:51.490
$36 billion, has $2 billion
invested in a company

00:24:51.490 --> 00:24:54.070
called Buy Post Investment.

00:24:54.070 --> 00:24:59.710
And they, in turn, have $911
million invested in COFINA

00:24:59.710 --> 00:25:01.440
in Puerto Rico.

00:25:01.440 --> 00:25:03.720
As an American, I
ask, shouldn't we

00:25:03.720 --> 00:25:07.530
learn more about how daily
decisions impact other US

00:25:07.530 --> 00:25:08.760
citizens?

00:25:08.760 --> 00:25:13.770
Shouldn't we think about solar,
water, and renewable energies,

00:25:13.770 --> 00:25:17.670
and how that investment
could maybe yield

00:25:17.670 --> 00:25:19.980
long-term and higher results?

00:25:19.980 --> 00:25:25.560
So I thank you for listening
to me, and for me sharing

00:25:25.560 --> 00:25:27.420
"Rosary Beads and Sundance."

00:25:27.420 --> 00:25:30.840
But I also want to
show you a little clip.

00:25:30.840 --> 00:25:35.730
For 14 years, I was part of
an incredible team at POV--

00:25:35.730 --> 00:25:37.860
point of view
documentaries-- and this

00:25:37.860 --> 00:25:41.100
shows you a little clip
of, a little taste,

00:25:41.100 --> 00:25:44.310
of what some of the most
powerful Latino filmmakers

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:45.700
are doing today.

00:25:45.700 --> 00:25:46.770
Thank you very much.

00:25:46.770 --> 00:25:48.243
[APPLAUSE]

00:25:48.243 --> 00:25:50.207
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:25:50.207 --> 00:25:53.644
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:25:53.644 --> 00:25:56.790
- This is going to happen
to any institution,

00:25:56.790 --> 00:25:59.536
and any oppressed community,
that does not respond

00:25:59.536 --> 00:26:00.660
to the needs of the people.

00:26:00.660 --> 00:26:03.310
- Part of my role as a
documentary filmmaker

00:26:03.310 --> 00:26:05.340
is to work for human rights.

00:26:05.340 --> 00:26:09.129
And I feel that my
work is not done yet.

00:26:09.129 --> 00:26:11.394
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:26:11.394 --> 00:26:15.250
- In this situation,
somebody in the place

00:26:15.250 --> 00:26:18.640
has got to have courage
to risk everything.

00:26:18.640 --> 00:26:22.092
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:26:22.092 --> 00:26:24.380
- Let go of my camera.

00:26:24.380 --> 00:26:27.160
Let go of my camera.

00:26:27.160 --> 00:26:30.596
- I felt that the documentary
could be the most immediate way

00:26:30.596 --> 00:26:32.345
to get to people, to
make them understand,

00:26:32.345 --> 00:26:35.980
to see and actually
feel what was going on.

00:26:35.980 --> 00:26:38.940
- Workers started coming in
to the garment workers' center

00:26:38.940 --> 00:26:42.180
with complaints about owed
wages, injuries on the job.

00:26:42.180 --> 00:26:45.180
- I was trying to get very
close with the characters,

00:26:45.180 --> 00:26:48.764
that you could
almost smell them.

00:26:48.764 --> 00:26:51.420
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:26:51.420 --> 00:26:52.840
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:27:05.870 --> 00:27:09.030
- I think a documentary
has the unique power

00:27:09.030 --> 00:27:12.820
to let you experience
someone else's life.

00:27:12.820 --> 00:27:15.100
- I knew something big
was going to happen.

00:27:15.100 --> 00:27:17.690
I knew I was going to get
some type of awakening.

00:27:17.690 --> 00:27:22.550
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:27:22.550 --> 00:27:24.780
- In many countries
in the world,

00:27:24.780 --> 00:27:27.491
governments do things that their
people wish they didn't do.

00:27:27.491 --> 00:27:31.140
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:27:31.140 --> 00:27:33.030
- Who are we, as Latinos?

00:27:33.030 --> 00:27:33.649
Do we matter?

00:27:33.649 --> 00:27:34.940
What's our role as an American?

00:27:34.940 --> 00:27:36.750
- Both my parents,
they came here

00:27:36.750 --> 00:27:40.200
to work, and to better the
lives of their children, of us.

00:27:40.200 --> 00:27:42.960
- What I really wanted to do
was capture the sense of humor

00:27:42.960 --> 00:27:46.136
and the culture behind
the economic crisis.

00:27:46.136 --> 00:27:56.489
[SINGING]

00:27:56.489 --> 00:27:58.640
- I love making
documentaries, and I

00:27:58.640 --> 00:28:00.845
want to keep making films,
and telling stories.

00:28:00.845 --> 00:28:03.920
- The camera illuminates
so many things.

00:28:03.920 --> 00:28:06.020
- On a personal level,
this film has changed me.

00:28:06.020 --> 00:28:08.150
- Without documentaries,
if we don't have that,

00:28:08.150 --> 00:28:09.862
if we can't look at
ourselves and see

00:28:09.862 --> 00:28:12.320
what's going on right now, how
do we know what's out there?

00:28:12.320 --> 00:28:13.403
- We don't need cover-ups.

00:28:13.403 --> 00:28:15.500
We don't need interference,
we need the truth.

00:28:15.500 --> 00:28:18.434
- Dear Selena, I
give you this letter

00:28:18.434 --> 00:28:22.346
so you would know that
lots of people love you.

00:28:22.346 --> 00:28:25.840
- We're showing the
power that we have.

00:28:25.840 --> 00:28:28.770
We're not a minority,
we're the majority.

00:28:28.770 --> 00:28:32.046
[CHEERING]

00:28:32.046 --> 00:28:33.960
- We are making films.

00:28:33.960 --> 00:28:35.910
We are talking
about our stories.

00:28:35.910 --> 00:28:38.770
People can now say, I
can make a documentary.

00:28:38.770 --> 00:28:41.240
And they can be a
part of my experience,

00:28:41.240 --> 00:28:44.402
and part of my culture,
and a part of me.

00:28:44.402 --> 00:28:45.866
[END PLAYBACK]

