00:30:13.090 --> 00:30:16.800
So I want to talk about
a couple of documentaries

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:21.720
that I made in, not my
past life, but a while ago.

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:23.910
Before Where Soldiers
Come From on POV,

00:30:23.910 --> 00:30:26.940
I made a couple of
films about immigration.

00:30:26.940 --> 00:30:30.430
And I was interested in
the topic of immigration

00:30:30.430 --> 00:30:33.480
for a lot of reasons, but I
worked for about eight years

00:30:33.480 --> 00:30:40.260
for various NGOs that worked
on immigrant refugee rights.

00:30:40.260 --> 00:30:44.370
Including, I worked in
the Rwandan refugee camps

00:30:44.370 --> 00:30:46.290
after the Rwandan genocide.

00:30:46.290 --> 00:30:48.720
And that was when
I decided I needed

00:30:48.720 --> 00:30:52.650
to be better able to tell
a story because of all

00:30:52.650 --> 00:30:53.970
the stories I had heard there.

00:30:53.970 --> 00:30:57.727
And that's when I came
back, and I did a film--

00:30:57.727 --> 00:30:58.560
well and I went to--

00:30:58.560 --> 00:31:00.490
I applied to film school.

00:31:00.490 --> 00:31:06.010
And that's what led
me down this path now.

00:31:06.010 --> 00:31:07.680
So the first documentary
I actually made

00:31:07.680 --> 00:31:11.070
was called Los Trabajadores,
and that was my thesis film

00:31:11.070 --> 00:31:13.614
at the University of Texas.

00:31:13.614 --> 00:31:15.780
And shortly after that, I
made a film called Letters

00:31:15.780 --> 00:31:17.250
From the Other Side.

00:31:17.250 --> 00:31:21.840
And they're both films
about Mexican migration--

00:31:21.840 --> 00:31:24.810
migration to the US from Mexico.

00:31:24.810 --> 00:31:28.580
One is from the
male point of view,

00:31:28.580 --> 00:31:31.170
and Letters From
the Other Side is

00:31:31.170 --> 00:31:33.130
from the woman's point of view.

00:31:33.130 --> 00:31:35.970
So, the two sides of
the immigration story.

00:31:35.970 --> 00:31:39.180
One is the husbands, the
fathers, the sons, and brothers

00:31:39.180 --> 00:31:43.230
who leave their families and
communities behind in Mexico

00:31:43.230 --> 00:31:45.990
to find work in the US, to
provide for the families

00:31:45.990 --> 00:31:47.280
they leave behind.

00:31:47.280 --> 00:31:50.857
And the other side, which
was often less talked about,

00:31:50.857 --> 00:31:52.440
is that of the women
and children left

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:58.260
behind when their husbands
and fathers migrate,

00:31:58.260 --> 00:32:01.230
and how their lives,
their responsibilities,

00:32:01.230 --> 00:32:03.610
and their roles change.

00:32:03.610 --> 00:32:08.100
They're all being
affected by these forces

00:32:08.100 --> 00:32:09.810
beyond their control.

00:32:09.810 --> 00:32:11.220
And it's not just
here in the US,

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:14.490
it's back home in
their home villages.

00:32:14.490 --> 00:32:17.520
So I want to start with a
clip from Los Trabajadores--

00:32:17.520 --> 00:32:19.430
The Workers.

00:32:19.430 --> 00:32:22.695
It was my first documentary,
as I said, my thesis film

00:32:22.695 --> 00:32:23.820
at The University of Texas.

00:32:26.580 --> 00:32:29.640
It came out in
2001, so I apologize

00:32:29.640 --> 00:32:34.440
for the 4:3 format
and the low quality,

00:32:34.440 --> 00:32:36.490
but that's what
it was back then.

00:32:36.490 --> 00:32:41.700
So just to give you a brief
background to the clip

00:32:41.700 --> 00:32:43.797
you're going to see.

00:32:43.797 --> 00:32:45.630
In Austin, where I was
going to grad school,

00:32:45.630 --> 00:32:49.230
there was a day laborer site
where immigrant day laborers

00:32:49.230 --> 00:32:52.230
would wait for work every day.

00:32:52.230 --> 00:32:56.610
And there was a lot of
grumbling from the people

00:32:56.610 --> 00:32:59.520
in that neighborhood about how
they didn't want this day labor

00:32:59.520 --> 00:33:01.920
site there.

00:33:01.920 --> 00:33:05.490
They didn't understand,
or know any of these men.

00:33:05.490 --> 00:33:09.500
And I thought, well, they
had a lot of misperceptions,

00:33:09.500 --> 00:33:12.890
and maybe one way that I could
fight these misperceptions

00:33:12.890 --> 00:33:16.130
is if I got to know
some of these men,

00:33:16.130 --> 00:33:19.190
and humanize the issue, and
told a story about them.

00:33:19.190 --> 00:33:23.910
So that's how I met Ramon,
who is the man you're

00:33:23.910 --> 00:33:26.760
going to see in this clip.

00:33:26.760 --> 00:33:29.640
I met him at the day labor site.

00:33:29.640 --> 00:33:31.980
He had come from Mexico.

00:33:31.980 --> 00:33:34.980
He was a husband to
Virginia, and the father

00:33:34.980 --> 00:33:39.090
of 19-year-old [INAUDIBLE],,
and 12-year-old [INAUDIBLE]..

00:33:39.090 --> 00:33:43.530
And this is just a short clip
that gives you a sense of him,

00:33:43.530 --> 00:33:46.726
and why he came to the US.

00:33:46.726 --> 00:33:49.600
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:33:49.600 --> 00:33:51.080
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:35:07.066 --> 00:35:09.010
[END PLAYBACK]

