00:36:41.051 --> 00:36:41.550
OK.

00:36:44.220 --> 00:36:48.300
So while I was making Los
Trabajadores, I went to Mexico,

00:36:48.300 --> 00:36:51.150
and I met Virginia and--

00:36:51.150 --> 00:36:54.180
Ramon's wife, Virginia,
and his two daughters.

00:36:54.180 --> 00:36:55.500
And it was--

00:36:55.500 --> 00:36:56.910
I wish I could
show clips of them

00:36:56.910 --> 00:36:58.950
but we don't have enough time.

00:36:58.950 --> 00:37:01.140
But it was through
them that I got

00:37:01.140 --> 00:37:05.400
the idea for my next
film, which is about women

00:37:05.400 --> 00:37:07.770
and children in Mexico
who have been left behind

00:37:07.770 --> 00:37:09.800
by the men who come to the US.

00:37:09.800 --> 00:37:11.550
Because I was really
struck by that.

00:37:11.550 --> 00:37:14.450
That it was something
that I, even,

00:37:14.450 --> 00:37:17.770
hadn't thought a lot about
until I met his family.

00:37:17.770 --> 00:37:19.980
And I feel like it wasn't
really a story that

00:37:19.980 --> 00:37:22.140
was talked about that much.

00:37:22.140 --> 00:37:26.670
So I started to do a lot of
research, and I was reading--

00:37:26.670 --> 00:37:28.982
and this was, like, 2003-ish.

00:37:28.982 --> 00:37:30.690
And I was reading a
lot about how there's

00:37:30.690 --> 00:37:33.270
whole villages in Mexico
where there's only women,

00:37:33.270 --> 00:37:34.650
and children, and old men left.

00:37:34.650 --> 00:37:38.040
There's no men, or
young men, left there.

00:37:38.040 --> 00:37:42.410
So that's when I decided
to go down to Mexico.

00:37:42.410 --> 00:37:45.400
And I met some--

00:37:45.400 --> 00:37:49.480
I met various women through
some different programs

00:37:49.480 --> 00:37:52.160
that work with women
in the villages there.

00:37:52.160 --> 00:37:57.100
And I followed--
well unlike Ramon,

00:37:57.100 --> 00:38:01.420
who was sending money
home all the time,

00:38:01.420 --> 00:38:03.250
the women I met there were--

00:38:03.250 --> 00:38:05.590
several of them were forced
to be, like, the breadwinner

00:38:05.590 --> 00:38:07.070
for their family.

00:38:07.070 --> 00:38:09.010
And it was, for
various reasons, I

00:38:09.010 --> 00:38:10.960
met two widows
whose husbands died

00:38:10.960 --> 00:38:15.050
in the biggest immigrant
smuggling case at the time.

00:38:15.050 --> 00:38:18.700
It was the truck that
had 100 men-- or, 100

00:38:18.700 --> 00:38:21.620
people in the back of it that
was stopped in Victoria, Texas.

00:38:21.620 --> 00:38:25.640
And so I met two widows of two
men who died in that truck.

00:38:25.640 --> 00:38:29.950
And even though they were
just grieving they still now

00:38:29.950 --> 00:38:32.200
were forced to think
about how they were going

00:38:32.200 --> 00:38:34.690
to provide for their children.

00:38:34.690 --> 00:38:38.350
And then I also met a
woman named Eugenia.

00:38:38.350 --> 00:38:41.150
And her situation was
much more complex.

00:38:41.150 --> 00:38:43.390
I mean, her husband
went to the US,

00:38:43.390 --> 00:38:46.180
and initially he was
sending money back,

00:38:46.180 --> 00:38:47.260
and keeping in touch.

00:38:47.260 --> 00:38:52.060
But it's very difficult for a
lot of people who come here,

00:38:52.060 --> 00:38:52.720
obviously.

00:38:52.720 --> 00:38:55.810
And I'm sure you
know why, and can--

00:38:55.810 --> 00:39:00.190
and so he kind of lost
his way, started drinking,

00:39:00.190 --> 00:39:03.190
and went down a bad
path, and sort of

00:39:03.190 --> 00:39:05.050
lost touch with his family.

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:07.360
And so Eugenia was then--

00:39:07.360 --> 00:39:09.820
kind of had to step up,
and try and figure out

00:39:09.820 --> 00:39:12.400
how to provide for her family.

00:39:12.400 --> 00:39:15.670
So I'm going to show
a clip of Eugenia.

00:39:15.670 --> 00:39:20.749
And, just to set up the
clip, it's a video letter.

00:39:20.749 --> 00:39:22.540
That's what the Letters
From the Other Side

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:27.220
is, which happened organically
when I was making the film.

00:39:27.220 --> 00:39:30.550
I was going back to Texas
to visit some friends,

00:39:30.550 --> 00:39:34.160
and Eugenia said, well, can
you visit my son in Arizona?

00:39:34.160 --> 00:39:36.460
And can you show him the
videos that I've been-

00:39:36.460 --> 00:39:37.930
that you've been making of me?

00:39:37.930 --> 00:39:39.596
And that's when I
realized how messed up

00:39:39.596 --> 00:39:42.430
it was that I could go visit
her son, a complete stranger,

00:39:42.430 --> 00:39:45.250
and she can't visit her son
because she lives in Mexico,

00:39:45.250 --> 00:39:46.900
and she can't cross the border.

00:39:46.900 --> 00:39:50.230
So it became a part of the film
where I would go back and forth

00:39:50.230 --> 00:39:52.370
with these video letters.

00:39:52.370 --> 00:39:55.030
So this is one clip
I'm going to show--

00:39:55.030 --> 00:39:57.670
it's actually one scene that
I broke into two small clips

00:39:57.670 --> 00:40:00.990
because it's too long
to play the whole scene.

00:40:00.990 --> 00:40:03.670
So we'll just show the first
part of the scene, and then

00:40:03.670 --> 00:40:05.494
the second part.

00:40:05.494 --> 00:40:06.160
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:40:06.160 --> 00:42:15.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:16.275
[END PLAYBACK]

